1. e4 Nf6 {The starting position for the Alekhine Defense, named after the 
fourth chess world champion Alexander Alekhine who introduced it in the 1921 
Budapest tournament in games against Endre Steiner and Fritz Sämisch. Black 
tempts White's pawns forward to form a broad pawn centre, with plans to 
undermine and attack the white structure later in the spirit of hypermodern 
defence. Modern champions of the Alekhine Defense are grandmasters Shabalov, 
Baburin and especially Bortnyk who use the opening with regularity, while 
Aronian, Adams, and Nakamura will use it on occasion. In the past, great players 
such as Fischer and Korchnoi included the defence in their repertoire, leading 
to its respectable reputation.} *

