1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 ({This is our first time seeing the more popular move 
order of} 3. d4 {followed by 4. c4. While we will present} 3... d6 {as Black's 
response here,} ({it should be noted that we offer the alternative 3... Nb6!? in 
our investigation of the mainline. If White is looking to play the exchange 
variation it will make little difference which move we play as after} 3... Nb6 
4. c4 {play will transpose when Black plays} 4... d6 {.})) ({We will later see} 
3. c4 {in the ‘Overzealous 4. c5’ and ‘Tate System’ sidelines.}) d6 4. 
c4 Nb6 {Reaching a slight crossroads. The main move here is exd6 - the aptly 
named 'Exchange Variation'. A secondary try for White is 4. f4 - the also aptly 
named '4-Pawns Attack' and this variation will be investigated later. Before we 
dive into the Exchange Variation, we will look at an understandably unpopular 
sideline try for White with 5. Nf3.} *

