1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 ({This is our first time seeing the more popular move 
order of} 3. d4 {followed by 4. c4. While we will present} 3... d6 {as Black's 
response here,}) ({it should be noted that we offer the alternative 3... Nb6!? 
in our investigation of the mainline. If White is looking to play the exchange 
variation it will make little difference which move we play as after} 3. d4 3... 
Nb6 4. c4 {play will transpose when Black plays} 4... d6 {.}) ({We will later 
see} 3. c4 {in the 'Overzealous 4. c5' and 'Tate System' sidelines.}) d6 4. c4 
Nb6 {Reaching a slight crossroads. The main move here is exd6 - the aptly named 
'Exchange Variation'. A secondary try for White is 4. f4 - the also aptly named 
'4-Pawns Attack' and this variation will be investigated later. Before we dive 
into the Exchange Variation, we will look at an understandably unpopular 
sideline try for White with 5. Nf3.} 5. Nf3 {We like to note Champions of the 
Alekhine throughout the text. GM Edvins Kengis is definitely another Alekhine 
player to seriously analyze. The stem game we used for this line was Gallagher - 
Kengis, 0-1, Bern 1992.} dxe5 ({While the most popular move in the database is} 
5... Bg4 {, we believe that it allows White to generate too much of an attack on 
our Kingside. This was also Taylor's conclusion in his book 'Alekhine Alert'.} 
6. Be2 e6 7. exd6 cxd6 8. O-O Be7 9. Nc3 O-O 10. Be3 Nc6 11. d5 {which is not 
fun to play.}) (5... g6 {would transpose directly into the 5...cxd6 Exchange 
Variation which is offered as an alternative line in the full course in the 
Exchange Variation chapter line with 5...g6.}) 6. Nxe5 g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Bf4 O-O 
9. Be2 Nc6 {Accepting the imbalance now seems to be the best option compared to 
our attempts with the immediate ...a5 which left White much better.} 10. Nxc6 
bxc6 ({Here we will briefly look at} bxc6 11. Be3 {.}) ({In the full course we 
also look at} bxc6 11. Be5 {.}) 11. Be3 {This move admits failure.} (11. Bf3 
Nxc4 {is fine for Black.}) Be6 12. c5 Nd5 13. Qd2 Rb8 14. Nxd5 Bxd5 15. O-O e5 
$15 {Black has a nice edge in this position.} *

