1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. exd6 {This is actually one of the 
easiest and most harmless variations of the Alekhine: Black can play against it 
with confidence as long as he remembers one specific move order and some general 
ideas.} exd6 ({The moves ...Nc6/...Bg4/...d6-d5, are our main focus. Black will 
get good counter-chances and can play for a win in a complex position if he 
accomplishes these moves. White's most common moves are the three obvious 
developments} exd6 6. Nc3 {,}) (exd6 6. Nf3) ({and} exd6 6. Bd3 {.}) ({The 
alternative to 5... exd6 is the symmetry-breaking} 5... cxd6 {. 5... cxd6 is a 
more 'combative' venture but it also undertakes more risk. We think both 
continuations are playable and while 5... exd6 is our main recommendation, we 
also investigate 5... cxd6 as an alternative try in the full course.}) 6. Nc3 
{The most popular move order. White is likely preparing to undertake the common 
Bd3 and Nge2 setup.} Nc6 {The 6... Nc6 move order is directed against White's 
main scheme of development in the position of Nc3, Bd3 and Ne2. It is critical 
to play ...Nc6 now and pressure the d4 pawn!} 7. Be3 {White protects the d4 pawn 
and intends to continue his original plan of development with Bd3 and Nge2.} Be7 
8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 Nb4 {This catches the light-squared Bishop with equality.} 
10. Bb1 Nxc4 11. a3 Nxe3 12. fxe3 Nc6 $17 {And Black is just a pawn up.} *

