1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 {Space has been taken by White, but pawns 
cannot go backwards. The entire principle of this opening is based on the 
concept of punishing overextension.} 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nf3 {Nf3 without h3 will 
pose difficulties for White (see Griffith - Tillis 0-1, Pro Chess League, 2019 
in the full course for an example game).} g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Be3 {Many moves by 
White will lead to the path Black wants.} O-O 9. Be2 Bg4 {White has given us 
full opportunity to play ...Bg4. This in all seriousness is going to be bad for 
his health. When Black has free reign to do what he will in the position, White 
will be dealing with a large number of practical problems... Let's be 
nettlesome!} 10. O-O Nc6 11. b3 d5 12. c5 Nc8 13. Rc1 {By far the most common 
reaction by white compared to the previous variation. Typically, if White has 
reached this position he is completely oblivious to the danger of Black getting 
the Alekhine Dream Position.} e6 14. h3 Bxf3 {This is only helping us reach our 
goal: White wasted a tempo convincing us to do something we already needed to 
do, how kind. :-)} 15. Bxf3 N8e7 16. Ne2 Nf5 {We have reached the Alekhine Dream 
Position! Notice how all of Black's pieces coordinate against the weak d4-pawn.} 
17. Qd2 Nh4 {White is bottled up trying to hold on to the weakness on d4 
creating problems elsewhere...} 18. Bg4 h5 19. Bg5 Bf6 ({This follows the game 
Miller -Tillis 0-1, 2008, Orlando After Memorial Open, where Black has an 
annoying edge and White has only bad options here as seen in the video content. 
White has the choice to play} Bf6 20. Bxf6 {which will lead to doubled pawns and 
a much worse position,}) ({or to play} Bf6 20. Bxh4 {which will lead to ...Bg5 
and a skewer which is only going to be fun for the second player.}) *

