1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 {The Classical Main line is considered the 
most theoretically challenging variation.} dxe5 {The most solid option at 
Black's disposal. Black will employ a strategy similar to that in the 
Scandinavian Defense - he will develop his light-squared Bishop before playing 
...e6 and then create a solid setup without weakness. We intend to argue that 
White's space advantage is only symbolic and that we will have good chances to 
outlast our opponent.} 5. dxe5 ({Very rarely played compared to the mainline of} 
5. Nxe5 {. However, it does have a presence at the club level.}) Bg4 ({From here 
in the larger course we will consider a couple moves:} Bg4 6. h3 {,}) (Bg4 6. 
Bc4 {,}) ({and the forcing} Bg4 6. c4 {.}) (5... Bf5 {should not be considered 
due to an awkward continuation:} 6. Nd4 {The critical variation} g6 {is the 
engine's first choice and this already signals that something has gone wrong.} 
7. Nxf5 gxf5 8. e6 fxe6 9. Qh5 {is no fun for Black.}) 6. Bc4 e6 7. O-O Nc6 8. 
Bb5 Qd7 9. c4 Ndb4 {The Queen trade isn't a concern. Black is fine tactically 
and we prefer the endgame anyways since the e5-pawn is a bit weak.} 10. Qxd7+ 
Kxd7 11. Nc3 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Rd8 13. Rd1+ Kc8 14. Rxd8+ Nxd8 $15 {And Black has a 
slight edge due to the much better structure.} *

