1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 6. Be2 Bf5 7. g4 {An 
aggressive move. To quote a previous author of the Alekhine: 'My conclusion 
after researching the Alekhine is that only the positional lines are worrisome 
for Alekhine's Defence players.' - Tim Taylor} Be6 ({White's main followup is 
the move} Be6 8. c4 {,}) ({but in the larger course we will also consider} Be6 
8. Rg1) ({and} Be6 8. f4 {.}) 8. c4 Nc7 ({After much debate, Carlsen's} 8... Nc7 
{is our recommendation due to the counterchances generated against White's 
overextended position.}) ({Also possible was} 8... Nb6 {which was featured in 
the high level game: Kasparov, Garry - Short, Nigel D, 1/2-1/2, RUS-The World, 
2002.}) 9. Rg1 Nd7 10. Nf3 g6 11. Nc3 Bg7 12. Be3 O-O 13. Qd2 b5 {A pawn 
sacrifice to gain better control over the d5 square and also open up lines on 
the Queenside, so that White's king will become stranded in the middle of the 
board.} 14. d5 cxd5 15. cxb5 Nf6 16. Nd4 Bd7 17. g5 Nfe8 {White is overextended 
and Black will have the edge after uncoiling.} *

