1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 dxe5 5. Nxe5 c6 6. Be2 Bf5 7. O-O {We're 
finally hitting upon the absolute mainline of the Classical Variation.} Nd7 8. 
Nf3 {A necessary move for White. Black wanted to trade on e5 in order to 
over-extend the e-pawn and make it a target for attack.} e6 9. c4 N5f6 10. Nc3 
Bd6 ({This is more accurate than} 10... Be7 {because Black fights for control 
over e5.}) ({White has many playable moves here and in the larger course we do 
our best to look at all of them:} Bd6 11. Nh4 {is the main move,}) (Bd6 11. d5 
{,}) (Bd6 11. Re1 {,}) (Bd6 11. Be3 {,}) (Bd6 11. Bd3 {,}) ({and} Bd6 11. h3 
{are all alternatives for White.}) (10... h6 {Giving our light-squared Bishop a 
retreat square simply does not work as White can slam the center and complicate 
matters:} 11. d5 $1 {Black is very uncomfortable here, for example} 11... cxd5 
12. cxd5 Bc5 13. Nd4 Bxd4 14. Qxd4 exd5 15. Qe3 Be6 16. Qg3 Kf8 17. Be3 {is not 
a position we would enjoy playing, even with the temporary extra pawn.}) 11. Bd3 
Qa5 $5 12. Re1 O-O 13. Bxf5 Qxf5 14. Qe2 Rfe8 15. Nh4 Qg4 16. Qxg4 Nxg4 17. h3 
Ngf6 $10 *

