1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 ({Now is a good time to note as we have before that 
3... d6 isn't our only recommendation against the Classical Variation move 
order. One could also play the alternative} 3... Nb6 {here and this will be 
investigated as an alternative line in this Short & Sweet course.}) 4. Nf3 
({When looking in the database there are many moves at Black's disposal in this 
position. By far the most common historically is} 4. Nf3 4... Bg4 {. This 
example game will show you why we do not suggest it as the text 
recommendation.}) Bg4 5. Be2 {The logical mainline. Other authors have beaten to 
death side variations of this line to show that Black is equal or better. We 
simply want to show how troubling the critical variations are.} e6 6. O-O Be7 7. 
c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Be3 {Black hasn't had much room for variety in the line so 
far and now we have reached a Tabiya position with no decent options for Black. 
For example:} d5 10. c5 Bxf3 11. gxf3 {Creating a bind that Black will not be 
able to escape.} Nc8 12. f4 Nc6 13. b4 a6 14. Rb1 Bh4 15. Bd3 f5 16. Kh1 N8e7 
17. Rg1 $16 {White has easy attacking prospects and a clear plan.} *

