1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 Nb6 {An alternate try by Black over the more popular 
3... d6. The idea is to play for 4... d5!? rather than ...d6, develop the 
light-squared Bishop and then play ...e6 with an improved version of the French 
Defense where we haven't blocked in our own Bishop. So if the Classical 
Variation is White's most testing try against the Alekhine Defense, and this is 
the 'Anti-Classical' Variation, why didn't we make this our main recommendation 
over the traditional Classical Variation lines? Great question! In short, there 
is much less data available for these lines and consequently we will wade into 
uncharted waters more often. While we are certainly confident in our published 
content, we are also realistic and know that Theory for this line is going to 
evolve and this discouraged us from making it our main recommendation. That 
said, we have enjoyed greater success with this variation than in the 
traditional Classical Variation lines and wanted to offer it for you to learn!} 
4. Nf3 {The most natural move to a Main Line Classical player. White develops 
his Knight to its normal f3 square, under the impression that the game will 
transpose to normal positions. Black's next move insures that it doesn't.} d5 
({The core idea of 3... Nb6: We induce White into strange, Advance French-style 
positions. Of course, you could transpose into the Classical Variation with} 
4... d6 {, but you don't gain anything by using this move order for that 
variation.}) ({In the larger course we will consider all of White's logical 
moves:} d5 5. Nc3 {,}) (d5 5. Be2 {,}) (d5 5. h3 {,}) ({and the two most common} 
d5 5. Bd3) ({&} d5 5. exd6 {.}) 5. Bd3 Bg4 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 e6 8. O-O c5 9. c3 
Nc6 10. Be3 Na4 $5 {Improving on Atabayev, M. - Zhigalko, S., 0-1, World Blitz 
2016.} 11. Qe2 (11. b3 Nxc3 $1 12. Nxc3 cxd4) c4 $1 ({Makes sense because White 
can't play} c4 12. Bc2 {in this moment.}) 12. Qc2 Nxc3 13. Bxc4 Nxb1 14. Bb5 Rc8 
15. Raxb1 Be7 {Black is fine 0-1 (15) Atabayev,M-Zhigalko,S.} *

