1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 Nb6 4. a4 {One of the more critical variations as it 
has a different feel from the Tate variation.} a5 {In many previous lines of the 
Anti-Classical 3... Nb6, White had the opportunity to play a4 in a position and 
we didn't show it. This is because it would be tedious to constantly point out 
the a4 possibilities and because we can sum it all up in one sentence. When you 
see a4, play ...a5. Simple, right? Now please note that this is different from 
how we will treat the Tate Variation because there we have the additional option 
of attacking key squares.} 5. Ra3 d6 6. exd6 exd6 {We play ... exd6 rather than 
...cxd6 in order to not magnify the weakness on b5.} 7. Rg3 g6 8. Nc3 Bg7 {So 
far so normal.} 9. Bg5 f6 10. Be3 d5 {Black can plan on going ...Nc6, ...Bf5, 
...Qd7 and ...O-O-O.} *

