1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {This flexible move can be considered the Anti-Alekhine as 
White refuses to kick our Knight with the typical e5 pawn push. However, in 
openings where White does not apply immediate pressure, Black usually has 
multiple options to counterattack.} d5 ({Our choice here is perhaps the most 
testing move besides the other central push} 2... e5 {. If you already have 
experience with e4-e5 positions, then this transposition might be of interest to 
you.}) ({Another way to play would be with} 2... d6 {. The PalmBeachChess 
YouTube page has a series of videos on the Czech Pirc Defense for Black and if 
this possible transposition interests you then make sure to look at the 2... d6 
subvariation. We have a free YouTube series on this system: https://www. 
youtube.com/watch?v=e6Cy09hl4eY}) 3. e5 {Beginning the critical mainline of the 
chapter.} Nfd7 4. e6 {It is best to start with this move first as it can be 
delayed for a couple moves and we will want to note the transpositions. This 
move should be characterized in your mind as an attack which should be 
respected, but not feared. With accurate play, Black will navigate through 
White's attack and obtain an advantage from the extra pawn.} fxe6 5. d4 c5 {Must 
be included before any ...Nc6.} 6. dxc5 Nc6 7. Nf3 g6 8. h4 {White's most 
aggressive option.} Bg7 9. h5 Nxc5 10. hxg6 hxg6 11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 12. Bd3 {A scary 
but toothless position with accurate defense.} Kd7 ({Intending to meet} Kd7 13. 
Bxg6 $2 {with} 13... Qg8 {.}) 13. Bf4 Qf8 14. Bg3 Qh6 $15 {This covers g6 and 
has the threat of ...Qh1+, the best type of move: defense with a threat. Black 
had a slight edge in Benares de sa Leitao, Ricardo - Milos, Gilberto, 0-1, Mario 
Covas 1st.} *

