1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. f4 {The Four Pawns Attack is the most 
'aggressive' of the variations of the Alekhine. White overextends to prove 
something which can't easily be proven and in return Black gets greater than 
usual counterplay.} dxe5 ({The main move in the position. A secondary choice 
would be} 5... g6 {which has been a favorite of Alekhine Authors in the past.}) 
6. fxe5 Nc6 ({Our first choice in the move order as it applies direct pressure 
to the center immediately. 6... Bf5 may afford extra options to White and it 
also loses us our chance to play ...Bg4 if White plays an early Nf3. In the 
larger course we will look at a couple of 7th move alternatives to the mainline} 
Nc6 7. Be3 {:}) (Nc6 7. c5) ({and} Nc6 7. Nf3 {.}) (6... Bf5 7. Be3 Nc6 
{transposes.}) 7. Be3 {Is by far the main move and the only real option for 
White.} Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 {So far we have been following the mainline in the 
database. Now, the young master of the Alekhine, Oleksandr Bortnyk, plays an 
interesting idea:} Bb4 ({Notice the divergence from the sample game where 
Svidler played the main line of} 9... Be7 {which allowed Grischuk's} 10. d5 {. 
9... Bb4 actively fights against the d4-d5 push.}) 10. d5 $2 {If White insists 
he is much worse quickly.} exd5 11. Bxb6 axb6 12. cxd5 Nxe5 $1 {Beginning a very 
forced sequence.} 13. Nxe5 Qh4+ 14. g3 Qe4+ 15. Qe2 O-O 16. Qxe4 Bxe4 17. Rg1 
Rfe8 18. Nc4 Bc5 {And we win the rook.} *

