1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. d4 d6 5. f4 dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 ({The most popular 
continuation in the database and the move order we will end up recommending 
over} 6... Bf5 {.}) 7. Be3 ({The most accurate move as} 7. Nf3 {allows Black the 
option of} 7... Bg4 {. This will all be explored in the trainable variations in 
the larger course so we will move on for now.}) Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 Be7 {We 
will now be following the game: Grischuk, Alexander - Svidler, Peter, 0-1, World 
Cup ACP 3rd, 2009. This will be a demonstration of the move 9... Be7, which is 
the current mainline of the variation, and why we prefer the alternative 9... 
Bb4.} (9... Bb4 10. Be2 Na5 {This will be the focus of our main recommendation 
in this chapter.}) 10. d5 {It is not hard to understand why this is the most 
critical variation of the opening.} (10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 
{scores decently for Black.}) exd5 {Grischuk and Svidler will follow the forcing 
mainline for a bit.} 11. cxd5 Nb4 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. e6 fxe6 14. dxe6 Bc6 15. Qg4 
Bh4+ 16. g3 O-O $2 {By choosing a different move order Svidler left himself open 
for a big blow...} (16. Bxh1 {Is the mainline in the database and Svidler was 
lucky that his game transposed.} 17. O-O-O Qf6 18. gxh4 O-O 19. Bb5 c6 20. Bg5 
{and we've transposed back to the game.}) 17. O-O-O (17. Nxc6 $1 Nc2+ 18. Ke2 
Qd6 19. Qxh4 bxc6 20. Bxb6 Nxa1 21. Be3 Nc2 22. Qe4 Nxe3 23. Kxe3 Rab8 24. Bc4 
{Where White is crushing.}) Bxh1 18. gxh4 Qf6 19. Bb5 c6 20. Bg5 Qe5 21. e7 Rfe8 
$2 (21... Rf2 {is stronger.} 22. Be2 Bd5 {The following moves show that chaos 
can erupt from this variation:} 23. a3 c5 24. Ne6 Nc6 25. Nxg7 Rxe2 26. e8=Q+ 
Rxe8 27. Nxe8 Rg2 28. Bf4+ Rxg4 29. Bxe5 Rg2) 22. Rxh1 (22. Nf5 Nxa2+ 23. Nxa2 
h5 24. Qe2 Qxf5 25. Bd3 Bf3 26. Qf2 Qf7 27. Rf1 Nd5 28. Qg3 Nxe7 29. Rxf3 {and 
the extra material will be enough for White.}) cxb5 23. Nf3 Nd3+ 24. Kc2 Qd6 25. 
Rd1 Nf2 26. Rxd6 Nxg4 27. Rd4 Nf6 28. h5 Rxe7 29. h6 Rd7 30. Bxf6 gxf6 31. Rg4+ 
Kf7 32. Nxb5 Rc8+ 33. Nc3 Rg8 34. Rf4 Nd5 {And Grischuk resigned. Though this 
line does hold up with best play, the critical line d5 is very difficult to play 
at a high level.} *

