1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Nc3 {Rather than hitting our knight with a pawn, White 
tries to push us back while developing his own pieces.} Nxc3 {After looking at 
all potential alternatives, we found this to be the most promising continuation 
for Black.} 4. dxc3 (4. bxc3 {is also covered in detail in the larger course.}) 
Nc6 {This is our main recommendation and is a necessary move order as it will 
not always transpose. Black has a clear path to equality without many paths for 
White to try for an advantage.} 5. Nf3 d6 {And here White has a couple of 
options with his light-squared bishop.} 6. Bb5 Bd7 7. Qe2 Nxe5 8. Nxe5 dxe5 9. 
Qxe5 f6 {The key set-up in this variation. Black establishes himself in the 
center.} 10. Qh5+ {Otherwise Black will just play ...e5 and follow with ...Bd6.} 
g6 11. Qe2 e5 {Following 0-1 P.Markland-V. Korchnoi, Bath 1973. We will deviate 
on the next move.} 12. Be3 a6 {Black will improve his bishops with ... Bd6, 
...Qe7, ...Be6 and then decide where to castle.} *

