1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 {Overzealous (hence the title). This is when 
gaining space becomes over-extension. Just a little knowledge in the variations 
will allow Black to have easy play against White's structure.} Nd5 5. Bc4 
{Considering that White's pawns are committed to dark-squares, it is not in 
White's best interest to trade away the light-squared bishop. However, Black 
still has to decide how to defend our knight. We will likely end up defending 
with both the e6 and c6 pawns, but our choice is to start with the c6-pawn since 
it narrows White's possibilities.} c6 6. Nc3 e6 {Looks a bit funny, but our 
pieces will soon come to life and the hole on d6 is covered.} 7. Ne4 {The knight 
is headed for d6, but this is not a problem.} b6 8. Nd6+ Bxd6 9. cxd6 O-O 
{Black's next moves are natural.} 10. d4 Ba6 11. b3 f6 {This freeing break gives 
Black excellent chances. Since this is essentially our main line of this 
chapter, we will look at a few possibilities for White.} 12. Qe2 ({Putting 
pressure on a6. Games in the database have continued with} 12. Qe2 12... Qc8 {, 
but Black has a much stronger move here.}) fxe5 {A very nice tactical idea. 
Black sacrifices on a6, but White is not advised to even take once.} 13. Bxa6 
Nxa6 14. Qxa6 {In for a penny...} b5 {Not only cutting off White's retreat 
squares for his Queen, but also ...Nb4 is an immediate threat that has to be 
contended with.} 15. Qa3 Qh4 16. Qb2 Nb4 {Relentless pressure.} 17. Kd1 Nd3 18. 
Qe2 Qxd4 $19 {Pain.} *

