1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. a4 {A pioneer of this system was the 
'swashbuckling tactician' Emory Tate. With respect we dub this line the Tate 
Variation.} d5 ({An interesting move going outside of the well trodden waters 
of} 4... d6 {.}) ({The move} 4... a5 {is a knee jerk reaction to stop a4-a5, but 
experiences unique problems due to a certain try by White. Next we will present 
some informational lines giving a closer look at the moves as white has a few 
options here which we hammer out in the main course.}) 5. a5 {The first try we 
should consider.} (5. exd6 {The mainline, this is the most common move in 
theory. In these positions we typically want} g6 {to be played.}) (5. exd6 cxd6 
6. a5 N6d7 7. d4 g6 8. Nf3 Bg7 9. Be2 O-O 10. O-O Nf6 11. h3 d5 {Much like a 
Tarrasch, d5 is the Bane move...take a look at the Exchange Variation with cxd6 
to respect the significance. 0-1 (16) Volovikov,A (2275)-Kovalenko,I (2578) 
2011}) (5. c5 Nc4 {Hitting the e5-pawn} 6. d4 (6. Nf3 Bg4) Nc6 {There are some 
tricky lines associated with developing the light-squared Bishop here so we 
prefer this Knight move} ({For example} 6. Bf5 7. Qf3 e6 8. Bxc4 {becomes very 
complicated after} Be4 9. Bb5 c6 10. Qg3) 7. b3 N4a5 8. Nf3 Bg4 {Improving on 
the game: Volovikov, Anton - Kovalenko, Igor, 0-1, Yuzhny op, 2011 as we 
guarantee that our Bishop is developed outside the pawn chain} 9. Be2 b6 {And 
Black will look to increase pressure on the c5 pawn}) (5. b3 {is a rare move 
trying to secure the Queenside but we look at many moves in the full course as 
the play is quite interesting. Play could continue with} 5...d4 {in order to 
secure outpost squares and make White's development more difficult} 6. f4 {is 
considered the mainline as it secures the weak e-pawn.} 6... Nc6 {White has a 
couple schemes of development here that we deal with in the full course.}) Nxc4 
{For the moment Black is up a pawn.} 6. d4 {The most logical way to defend the 
e5 pawn. Now White might hope to trap our knight with b3.} Bf5 {With a nice 
tactical resource to defend against b3.} 7. b3 {If White doesn't play 7. b3 then 
Black will play ...c6 to attack the weak overextended a-pawn.} (7. Bd2 Nxd2) 
Nxa5 8. Rxa5 Bxb1 $17 {The point.} *

