1. e4 Nf6 2. Bc4 {Seen sometimes at the club level and very rarely otherwise.} 
Nxe4 ({Where Black is already better! Typically it is not suggested to go pawn 
hunting in the opening as it can be a waste of time felt later, but a free 
center pawn is hard to turn down.} 2... d5 {could be played if you feel 
discomfort in playing this line as typically it will transpose into our analysis 
from} (1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. exd5 Nxd5 {with the possibility of a 
transposition} 4. Qf3 c6 5. Bc4 e6 {.})) 3. Bxf7+ {Seems scary, but give the 
line a few more moves before you jump ship.} Kxf7 4. Qh5+ Kg8 5. Qd5+ e6 6. Qxe4 
d5 7. Qe2 c5 ({Begins a simple variation where Black is better.} 7... e5 $5 {is 
a nice pawn sacrifice that has been seen in correspondence games, but it seems 
unnecessary from a human/practical point of view. We can get a very good 
position without sacrificing a pawn!}) 8. f4 {Trying to emphasize Black's 
backwards pawn.} Bd6 9. d3 h6 {This move allows for the flight of the black King 
and White has no checks on the h7-b1 diagonal. Black will complete development 
and be better.} 10. Nf3 Kh7 11. O-O Rf8 12. Ne5 {White didn't have great options 
to defend the f4-pawn.} Nd7 13. c3 Nxe5 14. fxe5 Rxf1+ 15. Kxf1 Be7 {Following 
Vuckovic, Bojan - Golubovic, Boris, 0-1, Nova Gorica op 03rd, 1998. The Bishop 
pair and lead and development gave Black a nice advantage.} *

