1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. Bc4 {An early commitment of the Bishop.} Nb6 4. Bb3 d5 
{Not only is this a typical move that we will see again and again in the full 
Alekhine Defense - The Dark Knight Rises repertoire, it also makes a great 
impression here since it works to shut out the Bishop on b3.} ({The other main 
alternative is} 4... c5 $5 {but this will actually transpose into complicated 
theory from the Alapin Variation of the Sicilian and we would rather stick to 
typical Alekhine positions and structures.}) 5. d4 Bf5 {We will reach the 
typical 'improved' French position. No Bad Bishop, no problems.} 6. Ne2 {This 
time White tries to attack our bishop in a slightly more critical fashion.} e6 
7. Ng3 Bg6 8. O-O c5 9. c3 Nc6 10. f4 {White clearly wants to jump on us before 
we catch up in development.} cxd4 (10... Qd7 {might work as well.}) 11. cxd4 f5 
({We stop White from playing f5 by playing ...f5 ourselves. Here White has to 
choose which structure he wants. Here we consider} f5 12. Be3 {.}) ({In the full 
course we also consider what happens if White plays} f5 12. exf6 {- gives Black 
the edge immediately -} Qxf6 13. Be3 Bd6 {when Black can pressure the weak f4 
and d4 pawns.}) 12. Be3 Be7 13. Nc3 O-O {Black already has full equality.} 14. 
a3 Na5 15. Bc2 Rc8 $10 {Aiming to occupy the c4-outpost.} *

