1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 ({Here we will be looking at the} 3. d4 3... d6 4. f4 
{offline,}) ({but it should be noted that we also offer} 3. d4 3... Nb6 $5) {as 
an alternative line to the Classical Variation.) Early f4 advances from the 3... 
Nb6 move order are covered in our Classical Variation in the full course 
Alekhine Defense - The Dark Knight Rises.} d6 ({The main move and our main 
recommendation in the Classical Variation which continues with} d6 4. Nf3 {.}) 
4. f4 {Has been played a fair number of times but in reality it is just an 
inferior version of the 4-Pawns Attack mainline which includes the moves c4 and 
...Nb6 first. Here Black just has additional options compared to the 4-Pawns 
Attack positions.} dxe5 5. fxe5 c5 {In the 4-Pawns Attack chapter within the 
Alekhine Defense: The Dark Knight Rises we abstain from the variation with ...c5 
which we investigate in an example game by GM Shabalov. Our reasoning there is 
that it is very hard to meet the critical early d5 advance by White, but here we 
have no such problem. The difference here is that if White now tries to play for 
c4 and d5, our Knight can go to the b4-square rather than the b6-square.} 6. Nf3 
cxd4 ({Simple and strong.} 6... Bg4 {is a much riskier alternative:} 7. Bb5 Nc6 
8. c4 {is very awkward to meet.}) 7. Qxd4 Bf5 ({A better move order than} 7... 
Nc6 {because it cuts down on White's possibilities. Otherwise} 8. Qe4 {is an 
option for White and this leads to different positions since Black has to play 
8} ...g6 {to prepare ...Bf5.}) 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Nc3 e6 ({Reaching a bit of a 
crossroads. Here we look at the move} e6 10. Qa4 {,}) ({but in the full course 
Alekhine Defense - The Dark Knight Rises we also consider} e6 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. 
Qxd5 exd5 12. c3 a6 13. Ba4 Bc5 14. Bf4 O-O 15. O-O-O Be6 $10) ({and} e6 10. Bg5 
Qa5 {Pinning and attacking the c3-Knight while also threatening some ...Qxb5 
tactics} 11. Qc4 Rc8 {. This position we handle with much more depth in the full 
course.}) 10. Qa4 {Was played in Pelikian, Jefferson - Milos, Gilberto, 0-1, 
Itau Cup 450th Ann, 2004. Surprisingly, this move just loses a pawn.} Ndb4 11. 
Bxc6+ bxc6 {And there's nothing White can do about the c2 pawn. The game 
continued:} 12. Be3 Bxc2 13. b3 Qd3 {Nice active play. Hitting the Bishop and 
preventing castling for the moment.} 14. Bd4 Be7 15. a3 Bxb3 16. Qxb3 Nc2+ 17. 
Kf2 Nxd4 18. Rad1 Qxf3+ {0-1} *

