1. e4 Nf6 {A modern day champion of the Alekhine Defense is Olexandr Bortnyk. He 
has been instrumental in the creation of this text as he is a contemporary 
trailblazer of the opening. This 2600 rated GM uses the Alekhine as his main 
weapon against 1. e4, showing that the Alekhine is reputable enough to be in the 
repertoires of the world's elite.} 2. d3 d5 {Against most Alekhine Offlines & 
Sidelines we will be essaying an approach with ...d5. This both keeps our 
repertoire linear/accessible while also taking advantage of ...d5 often being 
the best response that doesn't transpose into a separate opening system. We will 
provide different options for Black in the main course of the text and 
informational variations, but typically what we suggest is the path towards the 
most dynamic position with the least amount of theory.} 3. Nd2 {Is the mainline 
as it is the typical opening approach for players of the King's Indian Attack.} 
dxe4 ({Is our chosen approach to handling the position.} 3... e6 {would simply 
transpose to the French Defense,}) ({and} 3... e5 {can also be played if you 
have King Pawn theory in your repertoire.}) 4. dxe4 {This position will be far 
removed from the typical position a Kings Indian Attack player wants to achieve. 
In the very least we feel Black gets a moral victory by playing this line. A 
philosophy of openings is very much not allowing your opponent comfort in their 
pet lines.} e5 ({Reaching our first real crossroads. We will consider} e5 5. g3 
Bc5 6. h3 {- If h3 is the first choice of the machine you already know Black is 
better.} (6. Bg2 Ng4 {Is very annoying for White:} 7. Nh3 O-O {Again Black is 
just simply better}) 6... O-O {Or any other reasonable developing move. Black 
has a great lead in development,}) (e5 5. Ngf3 {Critical as it makes a threat 
against e5 and the natural ...Nc6 is not best} Bc5 {Defending e5 tactically.} 
(5... Nc6 6. Bb5 {Presents Black with some difficulties.}) 6. Nxe5 Bxf2+ 7. Kxf2 
Qd4+ 8. Ke1 Qxe5 {Where White has lost the right to castle and Black stands much 
better}) ({and} e5 5. Bc4 {as the most reasonable tries by White in the complete 
course Alekhine Defense the Dark Knight Rises.}) 5. Bc4 ({Not the most accurate 
move order for White as} 5. Ngf3 {reaches the same position but requires Black 
to play precisely.}) Bc5 6. Ngf3 O-O ({Again, the e5-pawn is protected 
tactically:} O-O 7. Nxe5 Bxf2+ 8. Kxf2 Qd4+ 9. Kf1 Qxe5 {.}) 7. O-O Bg4 ({A 
testing try by Black that carries more risk. The alternative,} 7... Qe7 {, is 
very solid.}) 8. h3 ({While} 8. c3 {is the only move played in our database, we 
believe that this is a knee-jerk reaction that many players would have.}) Bh5 9. 
g4 Bg6 (9... Nxg4 {is always a consideration, but can't be recommended here as 
after} 10. hxg4 Bxg4 11. Be2 {, White can protect his Kingside in a timely 
manner.}) 10. Nxe5 ({Critical and tricky as the immediate} 10. Nxe5 10... Bxe4 
{is not the correct response by Black!}) Qd6 ({The only move as the immediate} 
10... Bxe4 {is a blunder due to} 11. Nxf7 $1 Rxf7 12. Nxe4 {.}) {Here Black's 
Queen avoids these tactics by reaching a protected square while having the 
additional point that White's knight can't move without allowing ...Qg3.} 11. 
Ndf3 Bxe4 {Now we are good to take on e4.} 12. Bf4 Nbd7 13. Qxd6 Bxd6 $10 {And 
Black is fine.} *

